Kubernetes¶

Kubernetes is a container orchestration tool—an open-source, extensible platform for deploying, scaling and managing the complete life cycle of containerized applications across a cluster of machines. Kubernetes is Greek for helmsman, and true to its name, it allows you to coordinate a fleet of containerized applications anywhere you want to run them: on-premises, in the cloud, or both.

Kubernetes Use Cases¶

  1. Microservices Management: Easily deploy, scale, and manage microservices-based applications with automated rollouts, rollbacks, and service discovery.
  2. Batch Processing: Run batch jobs and scheduled workloads such as data processing pipelines.
  3. Hybrid & Multi-Cloud Deployments: Orchestrate containers running across on-premises and multiple cloud providers for flexibility and reliability.
  4. Dev/Test Environments: Create isolated, reproducible environments for software development and testing, enabling rapid iteration.
  5. CI/CD Automation: Integrate with continuous integration and delivery pipelines to streamline software releases.
  6. Resource Optimization: Efficiently utilize hardware resources through dynamic scheduling and scaling based on demand.
  7. Self-Healing Applications: Automatically restart, replicate, or replace failed containers for resilient application uptime.

Components of Kubernets¶

Master node¶

API Server¶

The front-end of the cluster controls the overall cluster health by directing all of the messages between components. Local computers interact with the Kubernetes cluster using a client called kubectl.

Scheduler¶

This component assigns newly formed pods to a node and assigns workloads to specific nodes in the cluster. Controller-manager: This ensures that the cluster is functioning correctly and tracks the available capacity of each controller and other services in the cluster.

etcd¶

The distributed key-value store that maintains details about how Kubernetes needs to be configured.

Worker node¶

Worker nodes perform tasks requested by the control plane. They include the following components that run on every node to maintain running pods:

Kubelet¶

This software agent executes orders from the master node and ensures the containers are running and healthy.

Pods¶

Each pod represents a single instance of an application, and each is assigned a unique IP address. This enables applications to use ports. The pods are created and destroyed on the nodes as needed to keep the system stable.

Kube-proxy¶

This service maintains network rules on nodes.

Container runtime¶

This software, such as Docker, is responsible for starting and running containers.

Pros and Cons of Kubernetes¶

Pros:

  • Scalability: Easily scale applications up or down as needed.
  • High Availability: Ensures minimal downtime with self-healing and automatic container restarts.
  • Portability: Runs on various infrastructures, including private, public, and hybrid clouds.
  • Efficiency: Automates resource management and optimizes hardware usage.
  • Ecosystem: A large, active community with a wealth of tools and extensions.
  • Declarative Configuration: Enables infrastructure as code and version control.

Cons:

  • Complexity: Steep learning curve; initial setup and management can be challenging.
  • Resource Overhead: Kubernetes itself requires resources to manage clusters.
  • Debugging Difficulties: Troubleshooting can be complex due to the abstraction layers.
  • Security: Managing secure configurations requires expertise and constant vigilance.
  • Cost: Potentially higher costs due to over-provisioning or managing multi-node clusters.
